The point Hamilton makes isn't something like `the advent of branding` or any such nonsense. He is saying that if you allow `civil rights` for the scum of society, the result will be nationalization of reputation, which is to say that reputation will no longer be that tool which the individual uses to effect his control, on his domestic animals, his slaves, his children, his women and his state - but instead become an investment into the ersatz of the individual, from these things. No longer a country of individuals who, on the strength of their reputation, attract dogs, horses, blacks, children, females and politicians plus every other subhuman category in between ; but instead a country where citizens (or however you call the plebs, taxpayers ?) are given dogs, horses, females, ipads, cars, housing and whatelse by some sort of god-surrogate, and then the sum given of these things given them is purported to play the role of reputation. No longer `tell me who you are to know if I should follow you`, but instead `tell me what number twitter says about you so I know who you are`. 
Hamilton is correctly identifying the hole through which the night crawls in, even if he calls `jacobins` what we call socialists today (while they call themselves `liberals` and other such). If man is separated from his reputation, then the fiction of the god-ersatz becomes necessary, and more extensive and complicated mischiefs than have hitherto flowed from the three great scourges of mankind, War, Pestilence and Famine become unavoidable. He is plainly saying that if you allow what you have allowed, that if you put scum like Lincoln, and like Roosevelt into office, that if you permit misery like `civil rights` then the necessary result will be a country where no actual people may be found, but only surrogates, cheap plastic imitations. A country where the state is coopted into the impossible business of playing God, a state where human life, properly speaking, is impossible. A point otherwise extant in Romanian literature of the period, and no doubt in every other literature worth the mention in the period. Because back then, literature was still possible, as it is always possible among men.
Among men only.">xxiii</a></sup></p>
